[The symptoms mentioned are characteristic of cutaneous anthrax, and presumably from these 36 persons being involved in the slaughter and butchering of this affected cow, or in the distribution and purchasing of the meat. We have yet to hear of gastroenteric cases in the 3 villages.

Cutaneous anthrax responds well to antibiotic treatment but gastroenteric anthrax is usually lethal. Frankly I don't know any precautions the public can take as it is up to the owners of sick and dead cattle to not butcher them, and for the authorities to be on top of the risks and make sure that livestock are vaccinated. When there are human anthrax cases it is a result of a lack of veterinary responsibility. - Mod.MHJ

Maps of Tanzania can be seen at http://www.mapsofworld.com/tanzania/maps/tanzania-political-map.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4895132,58810. A district map of Kilimanjaro region can be seen at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilimanjaro_Region. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
